SIMPLE: imposing
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imposing
<hw>Im*pos"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Laying as a duty;
enjoining.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Adapted to impress forcibly; impressive; commanding;
<as>as, an <ex>imposing</ex> air; an <ex>imposing</ex>
spectacle.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Large and <xex>imposing</xex>
edifices.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bp. Hobart.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Deceiving; deluding; misleading.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imposing</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Imposing
<hw>Im*pos"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>The act of
imposing the columns of a page, or the pages of a sheet. See
<er>Impose</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Imposing stone</b></col> <fld>(Print.)</fld>, <cd>the
stone on which the pages or columns of types are imposed or made into
forms; -- called also <altname>imposing table</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imposingly</ent>⟦br⟧
